\'e2\'80\'9cWhence, great Telemachus! this lofty strain?\
(Antinous cries with insolent disdain):\
Portions like mine if every suitor gave,\
Our walls this twelvemonth should not see the slave.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
He spoke, and lifting high above the board\
His ponderous footstool, shook it at his lord.\
The rest with equal hand conferr\'e2\'80\'99d the bread:\
He fill\'e2\'80\'99d his scrip, and to the threshold sped;\
But first before Antinous stopp\'e2\'80\'99d, and said:\
\'e2\'80\'9cBestow, my friend! thou dost not seem the worst\
Of all the Greeks, but prince-like and the first;\
Then, as in dignity, be first in worth,\
And I shall praise thee through the boundless earth.\
Once I enjoy\'e2\'80\'99d in luxury of state\
Whate\'e2\'80\'99er gives man the envied name of great;\
Wealth, servants, friends, were mine in better days\
And hospitality was then my praise;\
In every sorrowing soul I pour\'e2\'80\'99d delight,\
And poverty stood smiling in my sight.\
But Jove, all-governing, whose only will\
Determines fate, and mingles good with ill,\
Sent me (to punish my pursuit of gain)\
With roving pirates o\'e2\'80\'99er the Egyptian main\
By Egypt\'e2\'80\'99s silver flood our ships we moor;\
Our spies commission\'e2\'80\'99d straight the coast explore;\
But impotent of mind, the lawless will\
The country ravage, and the natives kill.\
The spreading clamour to their city flies,\
And horse and foot in mingled tumults rise:\
The reddening dawn reveals the hostile fields,\
Horrid with bristly spears, and gleaming shields:\
Jove thunder\'e2\'80\'99d on their side: our guilty head\
We turn\'e2\'80\'99d to flight; the gathering vengeance spread\
On all parts round, and heaps on heaps lay dead.\
Some few the foe in servitude detain;\
Death ill exchanged for bondage and for pain!\
Unhappy me a Cyprian took aboard,\
And gave to Dmetor, Cyprus\'e2\'80\'99 haughty lord:\
Hither, to \'e2\'80\'99scape his chains, my course I steer,\
Still cursed by Fortune, and insulted here!\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
To whom Antinous thus his rage express\'e2\'80\'99d:\
\'e2\'80\'9cWhat god has plagued us with this gourmand guest?\
Unless at distance, wretch! thou keep behind,\
Another isle, than Cyprus more unkind,\
Another Egypt shalt thou quickly find.\
From all thou begg\'e2\'80\'99st, a bold audacious slave;\
Nor all can give so much as thou canst crave.\
Nor wonder I, at such profusion shown;\
Shameless they give, who give what\'e2\'80\'99s not their own.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
The chief, retiring: \'e2\'80\'9cSouls, like that in thee,\
Ill suits such forms of grace and dignity.\
Nor will that hand to utmost need afford\
The smallest portion of a wasteful board,\
Whose luxury whole patrimonies sweeps,\
Yet starving want, amidst the riot, weeps.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
The haughty suitor with resentment burns,\
And, sourly smiling, this reply returns:\
\'e2\'80\'9cTake that, ere yet thou quit this princely throng;\
And dumb for ever be thy slanderous tongue!\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
He said, and high the whirling tripod flung.\
His shoulder-blade received the ungentle shock;\
He stood, and moved not, like a marble rock;\
But shook his thoughtful head, nor more complain\'e2\'80\'99d,\
Sedate of soul, his character sustain\'e2\'80\'99d,\
And inly form\'e2\'80\'99d revenge; then back withdrew:\
Before his feet the well fill\'e2\'80\'99d scrip he threw,\
And thus with semblance mild address\'e2\'80\'99d the crew:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cMay what I speak your princely minds approve,\
Ye peers and rivals in this noble love!\
Not for the hurt I grieve, but for the cause.\
If, when the sword our country\'e2\'80\'99s quarrel draws,\
Or if, defending what is justly dear,\
From Mars impartial some broad wound we bear,\
The generous motive dignifies the scar.\
But for mere want, how hard to suffer wrong!\
Want brings enough of other ills along!\
Yet, if injustice never be secure,\
If fiends revenge, and gods assert the poor,\
Death shall lay low the proud aggressor\'e2\'80\'99s head,\
And make the dust Antinous\'e2\'80\'99 bridal bed.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
\'e2\'80\'9cPeace, wretch! and eat thy bread without offence\
(The suitor cried), or force shall drag thee hence,\
Scourge through the public street, and cast thee there,\
A mangled carcase for the hounds to tear.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
His furious deed the general anger moved,\
All, even the worst, condemn\'e2\'80\'99d; and some reproved.\
\'e2\'80\'9cWas ever chief for wars like these renown\'e2\'80\'99d?\
Ill fits the stranger and the poor to wound.\
Unbless\'e2\'80\'99d thy hand! if in this low disguise\
Wander, perhaps, some inmate of the skies;\
They (curious oft of mortal actions) deign\
In forms like these to round the earth and main,\
Just and unjust recording in their mind,\
And with sure eyes inspecting all mankind.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
Telemachus, absorb\'e2\'80\'99d in thought severe,\
Nourish\'e2\'80\'99d deep anguish, though he shed no tear;\
But the dark brow of silent sorrow shook:\
While thus his mother to her virgins spoke:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cOn him and his may the bright god of day\
That base, inhospitable blow repay!\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
The nurse replies: \'e2\'80\'9cIf Jove receives my prayer,\
Not one survives to breathe to-morrow\'e2\'80\'99s air.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
\'e2\'80\'9cAll, all are foes, and mischief is their end;\
Antinous most to gloomy death a friend\
(Replies the queen): the stranger begg\'e2\'80\'99d their grace,\
And melting pity soften\'e2\'80\'99d every face;\
From every other hand redress he found,\
But fell Antinous answer\'e2\'80\'99d with a wound.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
Amidst her maids thus spoke the prudent queen,\
Then bade Eumaeus call the pilgrim in.\
\'e2\'80\'9cMuch of the experienced man I long to hear,\
If or his certain eye, or listening ear,\
Have learn\'e2\'80\'99d the fortunes of my wandering lord?\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
Thus she, and good Eumaeus took the word:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cA private audience if thy grace impart,\
The stranger\'e2\'80\'99s words may ease the royal heart.\
His sacred eloquence in balm distils,\
And the soothed heart with secret pleasure fills.\
Three days have spent their beams, three nights have run\
Their silent journey, since his tale begun,\
Unfinish\'e2\'80\'99d yet; and yet I thirst to hear!\
As when some heaven-taught poet charms the ear\
(Suspending sorrow with celestial strain\
Breathed from the gods to soften human pain)\
Time steals away with unregarded wing,\
