\
She spoke. Telemachus then sneezed aloud;\
Constrain\'e2\'80\'99d, his nostril echoed through the crowd.\
The smiling queen the happy omen bless\'e2\'80\'99d:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cSo may these impious fall, by Fate oppress\'e2\'80\'99d!\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
Then to Eumaeus: \'e2\'80\'9cBring the stranger, fly!\
And if my questions meet a true reply,\
Graced with a decent robe he shall retire,\
A gift in season which his wants require.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
Thus spoke Penelope. Eumaeus flies\
In duteous haste, and to Ulysses cries:\
\'e2\'80\'9cThe queen invites thee, venerable guest!\
A secret instinct moves her troubled breast,\
