\
BOOK XXII.\
\
\
ARGUMENT.\
THE DEATH OF THE SUITORS.\
\
\
Ulysses begins the slaughter of the suitors by the death of Antinous.\
He declares himself, and lets fly his arrows at the rest. Telemachus\
assists and brings arms for his father, himself, Eumaeus, and\
Philaetius. Melanthius does the same for the wooers. Minerva encourages\
Ulysses in the shape of Mentor. The suitors are all slain, only Medon\
and Phemius are spared. Melanthius and the unfaithful servants are\
executed. The rest acknowledge their master with all demonstrations of\
joy.\
\
\
Then fierce the hero o\'e2\'80\'99er the threshold strode;\
Stripp\'e2\'80\'99d of his rags, he blazed out like a god.\
Full in their face the lifted bow he bore,\
And quiver\'e2\'80\'99d deaths, a formidable store;\
Before his feet the rattling shower he threw,\
And thus, terrific, to the suitor-crew:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cOne venturous game this hand hath won to-day,\
Another, princes! yet remains to play;\
Another mark our arrow must attain.\
Phoebus, assist! nor be the labour vain.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
Swift as the word the parting arrow sings,\
And bears thy fate, Antinous, on its wings:\
Wretch that he was, of unprophetic soul!\
High in his hands he rear\'e2\'80\'99d the golden bowl!\
E\'e2\'80\'99en then to drain it lengthen\'e2\'80\'99d out his breath;\
Changed to the deep, the bitter draught of death:\
For fate who fear\'e2\'80\'99d amidst a feastful band?\
And fate to numbers, by a single hand?\
Full through his throat Ulysses\'e2\'80\'99 weapon pass\'e2\'80\'99d,\
And pierced his neck. He falls, and breathes his last.\
The tumbling goblet the wide floor o\'e2\'80\'99erflows,\
A stream of gore burst spouting from his nose;\
Grim in convulsive agonies be sprawls:\
Before him spurn\'e2\'80\'99d the loaded table falls,\
And spreads the pavement with a mingled flood\
Of floating meats, and wine, and human blood.\
Amazed, confounded, as they saw him fall,\
Up rose he throngs tumultuous round the hall:\
O\'e2\'80\'99er all the dome they cast a haggard eye,\
Each look\'e2\'80\'99d for arms\'e2\'80\'94in vain; no arms were nigh:\
\'e2\'80\'9cAim\'e2\'80\'99st thou at princes? (all amazed they said;)\
Thy last of games unhappy hast thou play\'e2\'80\'99d;\
Thy erring shaft has made our bravest bleed,\
And death, unlucky guest, attends thy deed.\
Vultures shall tear thee.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157  Thus incensed they spoke,\
While each to chance ascribed the wondrous stroke:\
Blind as they were: for death e\'e2\'80\'99en now invades\
His destined prey, and wraps them all in shades.\
Then, grimly frowning, with a dreadful look,\
That wither\'e2\'80\'99d all their hearts, Ulysses spoke:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cDogs, ye have had your day! ye fear\'e2\'80\'99d no more\
Ulysses vengeful from the Trojan shore;\
While, to your lust and spoil a guardless prey,\
Our house, our wealth, our helpless handmaids lay:\
Not so content, with bolder frenzy fired,\
E\'e2\'80\'99en to our bed presumptuous you aspired:\
Laws or divine or human fail\'e2\'80\'99d to move,\
Or shame of men, or dread of gods above;\
Heedless alike of infamy or praise,\
Or Fame\'e2\'80\'99s eternal voice in future days;\
The hour of vengeance, wretches, now is come;\
Impending fate is yours, and instant doom.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157 \
\
Thus dreadful he. Confused the suitors stood,\
From their pale cheeks recedes the flying blood:\
Trembling they sought their guilty heads to hide.\
Alone the bold Eurymachus replied:\
\
\'e2\'80\'9cIf, as thy words import (he thus began),\
Ulysses lives, and thou the mighty man,\
Great are thy wrongs, and much hast thou sustain\'e2\'80\'99d\
In thy spoil\'e2\'80\'99d palace, and exhausted land;\
The cause and author of those guilty deeds,\
Lo! at thy feet unjust Antinous bleeds\
Not love, but wild ambition was his guide;\
To slay thy son, thy kingdom to divide,\
These were his aims; but juster Jove denied.\
Since cold in death the offender lies, oh spare\
Thy suppliant people, and receive their prayer!\
Brass, gold, and treasures, shall the spoil defray,\
Two hundred oxen every prince shall pay:\
The waste of years refunded in a day.\
Till then thy wrath is just.\'e2\'80\uc0\u157  Ulysses burn\'e2\'80\'99d\
With high disdain, and sternly thus return\'e2\'80\'99d:\
